transcendence style.

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:52.560
So we've got mindfulness.

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:54.620
And then we've got a
self-induced transcendence

00:09:54.620 --> 00:09:56.320
style of meditation.

00:09:56.320 --> 00:09:59.540
Now, mindfulness is more
of a waking state practice.

00:09:59.540 --> 00:10:01.820
It's generally taught over
the course of eight weeks.

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:03.580
You meet once a week
for eight weeks.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:05.590
And it can be quite gentle.

00:10:05.590 --> 00:10:08.812
And the results are a bit more
gradual because it's something

00:10:08.812 --> 00:10:10.770
that you're integrating
into your waking state.

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:13.050
It's basically the practice
of bringing yourself back

00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:14.280
into the now.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:15.780
So if you're
walking, you're like,

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:20.240
here I am, walking, I'm walking,
I am walking, I'm sitting,

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:22.690
I am sitting, I am-- here I
am, sit-- I'm washing dishes,

00:10:22.690 --> 00:10:24.190
here I am washing
dishes, I'm really

00:10:24.190 --> 00:10:26.690
feeling the water
flowing over my hands.

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:28.420
And this sounds very simple.

00:10:28.420 --> 00:10:30.930
But if you think about how
much we're multitasking

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:33.510
and how much information
our brains are ingesting

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:37.770
all of the time,
largely due to you guys,

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:40.170
this idea of doing
one thing at a time

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:41.950
actually becomes quite novel.

00:10:41.950 --> 00:10:43.980
We actually have to start
to retrain ourselves

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:47.140
to single-task,
which, I would argue,

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:50.530
gives you more computing
power for the task at hand.

00:10:50.530 --> 00:10:53.880
Now mindfulness is derivative
of a monastic practice.

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:56.310
It was originally
developed for monks.

00:10:56.310 --> 00:10:58.310
And this was news to
me because I always

00:10:58.310 --> 00:11:00.810
thought that whatever
monks were practicing

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:03.500
must be much more powerful
than what people like

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:05.580
us would practice because
they're monks, right?

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:07.520
So they must be, like,
levitating or floating

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:10.050
or, like, gaining enlightenment
on their first day.

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:11.850
But it's actually the opposite.

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:15.000
If you're a monk, then your
contribution to society

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:15.600
is meditating.

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:18.346
You have the time to
meditate, basically, all day.

00:11:18.346 --> 00:11:20.220
If you're walking, it's
a walking meditation.

00:11:20.220 --> 00:11:22.420
If you're gardening, it's
a gardening meditation.

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:25.060
And this is their
contribution to society,

00:11:25.060 --> 00:11:29.270
whereas something that we
might practice is different.

00:11:29.270 --> 00:11:32.292
Now, in India, you're either a
monk or you're a householder.

00:11:32.292 --> 00:11:34.000
And it doesn't do you
any good to pretend

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.541
to be a monk if
you're a householder.

00:11:35.541 --> 00:11:37.490
And when I say householder,
I basically mean,

00:11:37.490 --> 00:11:40.600
so we have a job and a
family and stuff to do.

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:43.460
So if you are a householder,
you have less time

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:47.484
in your day with
which to meditate,

00:11:47.484 --> 00:11:48.900
which actually
means that you need

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:51.380
to practice something that
is a bit more powerful.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:53.588
You have less time in the
day with which to meditate,

00:11:53.588 --> 00:11:55.410
so you need to really
go in and clean house

00:11:55.410 --> 00:11:57.730
so that you can deliver that
fulfillment to your day.

00:11:57.730 --> 00:11:59.920
So you're like, y'all, I've got
stuff to do-- all I can do is,

00:11:59.920 --> 00:12:01.190
like, come in, I've got
to answer some emails,

00:12:01.190 --> 00:12:03.648
and eat my lunch while I listen
to this meditation caffeine

00:12:03.648 --> 00:12:05.930
talk, and hopefully, it'll
make me get more done.

00:12:05.930 --> 00:12:08.590
And ultimately, it will.

00:12:08.590 --> 00:12:13.010
Point of the story is that all
meditation is good for you.

00:12:13.010 --> 00:12:15.270
But there are two main
branches, and they

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:19.960
come from different
styles of meditation.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:21.660
Now, obviously I'm
biased, OK, because I

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:23.830
teach this self-induced
transcendence

00:12:23.830 --> 00:12:27.120
style of meditation, and
it's totally changed my life.

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:30.220
So I'd love to say that this
was a non-biased account

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:32.470
of the differences between
the two, but spoiler alert,

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:35.107
it's 100% biased.

00:12:35.107 --> 00:12:37.190
But this self-induced
transcendence style-- you're

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:40.290
basically accessing a fourth
state of consciousness,

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:43.380
different than waking, different
than sleeping, and different

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:46.940
than dreaming, where the right
and left parts of your brain

00:12:46.940 --> 00:12:48.769
start to function in unison.

00:12:48.769 --> 00:12:50.310
Now, the good news
is that regardless

00:12:50.310 --> 00:12:53.150
of what style of meditation
you're practicing,

00:12:53.150 --> 00:12:55.510
they are both going to
have a lot of benefits.

00:12:55.510 --> 00:12:58.240
One is the ability to be more
present in the right now.

00:12:58.240 --> 00:13:00.460
Two is that it actually--
both styles of meditation

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:03.146
are going to
increase the strength

00:13:03.146 --> 00:13:04.770
and, really, the
thickness of something

00:13:04.770 --> 00:13:06.990
called the corpus callosum.

00:13:06.990 --> 00:13:09.890
Now, the corpus callosum is
this thin strip of white matter

00:13:09.890 --> 00:13:11.240
that connects the gray matter.

00:13:11.240 --> 00:13:13.710
It is the bridge between the
right and left hemispheres

00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:15.380
of your brain.

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:18.290
So we've known for a long time
that meditators have thicker

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:20.360
corpus callosums
than non-meditators,

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:23.510
but we weren't able to prove
if it was causal or correlated.

00:13:23.510 --> 00:13:26.310
Now, because we have
advances in neuroscience,

00:13:26.310 --> 00:13:28.660
we now know that the
longer you meditate,

00:13:28.660 --> 00:13:31.110
the thicker this
corpus callosum gets.

00:13:31.110 --> 00:13:32.680
Cool party trick, but who cares?

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:34.720
Why would anyone want
a fat corpus callosum?

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:36.550
Well, everyone should.

00:13:36.550 --> 00:13:37.480
And here's why.

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:39.480
Here's a Cliff's Notes
version of the difference

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.340
between the right
and left brains.

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:45.500
Your left brain is in charge
of the past and the future.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:47.410
It's in charge of
language, critical thought,

00:13:47.410 --> 00:13:51.190
analytical thought, math,
balancing your checkbooks-- all

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:53.240
really important activities,
but for most of us,

00:13:53.240 --> 00:13:55.531
we've been taking our left
brain to the gym, especially

00:13:55.531 --> 00:13:56.760
you guys.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:58.810
Just think, take action,
achieve, make money,

00:13:58.810 --> 00:14:00.560
so you can be happy
in the future--

00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:02.750
really working out this
past, future muscle.

00:14:02.750 --> 00:14:05.750
Meanwhile, our poor little
right brains are atrophy.

00:14:05.750 --> 00:14:07.810
Now, your right brain
is the piece of you

00:14:07.810 --> 00:14:09.890
that's in charge
of the right now.

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:12.830
It's the piece of you that
is in charge of intuition,

00:14:12.830 --> 00:14:16.410
inspiration, creativity,
music, connectedness.

00:14:16.410 --> 00:14:18.990
And it is the place that you
get your creative problem

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:20.200
solving ideas.

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:23.570
It is the place where
you get those downloads.

00:14:23.570 --> 00:14:26.840
So I think that any conversation
about productivity, especially

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:29.860
in a field where innovation
is currency, then meditation

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:32.010
has to be a part of
that conversation

00:14:32.010 --> 00:14:34.760
because while we have been
valuing this left brain

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:37.570
analytical part of our
mind for far too long,

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:38.970
it's gotten out of balance.

00:14:38.970 --> 00:14:41.735
You know, if you look at
a human brain, it's 50/50.

00:14:41.735 --> 00:14:43.610
And I don't think that
nature makes mistakes.

00:14:43.610 --> 00:14:44.984
I don't think that
nature gave us

00:14:44.984 --> 00:14:48.609
50/50 of a brain if it
wanted us to use 90/10.

00:14:48.609 --> 00:14:50.400
So all we're doing when
we're meditating is

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:52.024
that we're taking
our brain to the gym.

00:14:52.024 --> 00:14:53.930
You're strengthening
this corpus callosum,

00:14:53.930 --> 00:14:55.800
which is going to
allow you to come up

00:14:55.800 --> 00:14:58.110
with these creative
problem solving ideas,

00:14:58.110 --> 00:15:00.121
even when you're in a
high stress situation.

00:15:00.121 --> 00:15:01.870
So your boss is yelling
at you, and you've

00:15:01.870 --> 00:15:03.780
got a really short
deadline-- instead

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:05.886
of going into panic mode
and fight or flight,

00:15:05.886 --> 00:15:07.510
you're going to be
able to still access

00:15:07.510 --> 00:15:12.311
this whole other realm of
creativity and inspiration.

00:15:12.311 --> 00:15:13.310
Sounds pretty good, huh?

00:15:21.470 --> 00:15:25.930
Call me crazy, but I
don't think that stress

00:15:25.930 --> 00:15:27.640
makes you more productive.

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:29.015
A lot of people
say that it does.

00:15:29.015 --> 00:15:31.220
I teach a lot of CEOs, and
I teach a lot of actors,

00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:33.170
and they have two
different stories.

00:15:33.170 --> 00:15:35.420
My CEO clients will say,
Emily, I need my stress,

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:37.190
I need my angst, that
is the thing that

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:39.135
gives me my competitive edge.

00:15:39.135 --> 00:15:40.580
No, it is not.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:42.040
That is just false.

00:15:42.040 --> 00:15:44.680
And I'm going to explain
why, in just a moment.

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:47.790
And with my actor clients, they
say, Emily, I need my stress,

00:15:47.790 --> 00:15:50.650
I need my angst because this
is where I get my creativity,

00:15:50.650 --> 00:15:52.770
this is where I
draw from my work.

00:15:52.770 --> 00:15:53.270
Nope.

00:15:53.270 --> 00:15:54.010
No, it is not.

00:15:54.010 --> 00:15:56.900
You get your creativity from
this right part of your brain.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:58.320
We think our ideas are our own.

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:00.760
Our ego gets involved, and
it's like, it's my idea.

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:01.260
Nope.

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:02.676
You're just
downloading that thing

00:16:02.676 --> 00:16:05.640
from this beautiful,
creative cloud in the sky.

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:07.400
Getting a little
altruistic for Google.

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:10.410
I'm going to move on.

00:16:10.410 --> 00:16:12.150
Let's move on to our
third point which

00:16:12.150 --> 00:16:14.930
is when can stress
actually serve you?

00:16:14.930 --> 00:16:17.430
When can stress actually
be good for you?

00:16:17.430 --> 00:16:19.780
Stress is getting sort
of a bad rap, these days.

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:22.430
It's being called the Black
Plague of our century.

00:16:22.430 --> 00:16:24.830
And I don't think that that
is an over-exaggeration.

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:26.490
I would agree with
that statement.

00:16:26.490 --> 00:16:28.280
However, there are times
that stress is good for you,

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:29.613
and I'm going to get into those.

00:16:29.613 --> 00:16:32.750
But first, we've got to
understand how and why stress

00:16:32.750 --> 00:16:34.702
affects our body in
the way that it does.

00:16:34.702 --> 00:16:36.160
And in order to
understand that, we

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:38.037
have to go back in time
a few thousand years

00:16:38.037 --> 00:16:40.370
and say we're, like, hunting
and gathering in the woods.

00:16:40.370 --> 00:16:42.870
I don't know why this is the
move for hunting and gathering,

00:16:42.870 --> 00:16:43.870
but just go with it.

00:16:43.870 --> 00:16:44.890
So say we're hunting
and gathering,

00:16:44.890 --> 00:16:46.930
and out of nowhere,
this saber-toothed tiger

00:16:46.930 --> 00:16:49.940
jumps out at you and
with the intent to kill.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:52.870
So your body is going to launch
into a series of chemical

00:16:52.870 --> 00:16:53.870
reactions.

00:16:53.870 --> 00:16:56.810
First, your digestion is going
to flood with acid to shut down

00:16:56.810 --> 00:17:00.140
digestion because it takes a lot
of energy to digest your food

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:02.550
and you need all hands
on deck to fight or flee

00:17:02.550 --> 00:17:04.280
this predatory attack.

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:06.425
That same acid will
then seep into your skin

00:17:06.425 --> 00:17:08.550
so that you don't taste
very good if you get bitten

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:10.310
into by that tiger.

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:12.319
Your blood will start
to thicken and coagulate

00:17:12.319 --> 00:17:14.880
so that if you get bitten
into, you don't bleed to death.

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.069
Your vision will go
from here to here

00:17:17.069 --> 00:17:19.440
so that you're not distracted
from your opponent.

00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:21.119
Your bladder and
bowels will evacuate

00:17:21.119 --> 00:17:22.494
so that you're
light on your feet

00:17:22.494 --> 00:17:23.720
so you could fight or flee.

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:25.430
So the nervous poos you
get before an audition

00:17:25.430 --> 00:17:26.410
or like a-- or you guys
don't have auditions,

00:17:26.410 --> 00:17:29.160
but like a presentation,
that's your body trying

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:31.190
to protect you.

00:17:31.190 --> 00:17:33.330
Your heart rate will increase.

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:33.830
See?

00:17:33.830 --> 00:17:35.580
People are laughing
because they identify.

00:17:37.880 --> 00:17:39.180
Your heart rate will increase.

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:41.320
Your cortisol levels
will increase.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:44.172
And your immune system
will go to the back burner

00:17:44.172 --> 00:17:46.130
because who cares if
you're going to get cancer

00:17:46.130 --> 00:17:48.740
if you're about to
be killed by a tiger?

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:51.420
Again, we need all hands
on deck to fight or flee

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.080
this predatory attack.

00:17:53.080 --> 00:17:56.330
So this series of chemical
reactions is very good for you.

00:17:56.330 --> 00:18:00.275
It is very useful if your
demands are predatory attacks.

00:18:02.582 --> 00:18:04.540
Now, I don't know when
the last time any of you

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:06.390
guys got attacked
by a tiger was.

00:18:06.390 --> 00:18:08.632
But my guess is it
wasn't very recently.

00:18:08.632 --> 00:18:10.840
Now, obviously, there are
some high demand situations

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:12.500
where it's good for your
body to get stressed.

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:14.240
If you get into a car
accident, or if you

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:16.610
get jumped in the back
alleyway, or if you

00:18:16.610 --> 00:18:18.490
need to lift a
car off of a baby,

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:21.320
these are all great times for
your body to get stressed.

00:18:21.320 --> 00:18:23.410
And this series of
chemical reactions

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:24.700
is really going to serve you.

00:18:24.700 --> 00:18:26.780
It's actually not bad
for your body to get

00:18:26.780 --> 00:18:32.570
stressed-- it is toxic for
your body to stay stressed.

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:34.490
This fight or flight
thing-- yes, great.

00:18:34.490 --> 00:18:35.990
It's good for it to happen.

00:18:35.990 --> 00:18:38.480
But then, if it's a
few thousand years ago,

00:18:38.480 --> 00:18:40.870
and you're actually
engaging in fighting a tiger

00:18:40.870 --> 00:18:42.920
or outrunning a
tiger, then you get

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:44.731
to burn off those
stress chemicals.

00:18:44.731 --> 00:18:46.480
And this is why a lot
of people say to me,

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:49.430
well, Emily, exercise
is my meditation.

00:18:49.430 --> 00:18:51.150
No, it's not.

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:52.750
Exercise is exercise.

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:54.042
Meditation is meditation.

00:18:54.042 --> 00:18:56.250
They do very different things
to your nervous system.

00:18:56.250 --> 00:18:59.110
When you exercise, you
excite your nervous system.

00:18:59.110 --> 00:19:01.170
You increase your
metabolic rate.

00:19:01.170 --> 00:19:04.070
When you meditate, you
de-excite your nervous system,

00:19:04.070 --> 00:19:06.350
and you decrease
your metabolic rate.

00:19:06.350 --> 00:19:07.920
Now, exercise is great for you.

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:09.580
When you get in the treadmill
and you start running,

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:11.371
you can outrun that
tiger, you can burn off

00:19:11.371 --> 00:19:13.405
the stress chemicals from today.

00:19:13.405 --> 00:19:15.530
You get in a boxing ring,
you can fight that tiger,

00:19:15.530 --> 00:19:17.984
and you can burn off the
stress chemicals from today.

00:19:17.984 --> 00:19:20.400
But if you want to handle the
dog that barked in your face

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:22.420
when you were seven or the fight
that your parents got in when

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:24.180
you were 10, then
you actually have

00:19:24.180 --> 00:19:25.629
to de-excite your
nervous system.

00:19:25.629 --> 00:19:27.045
So basically, what
I'm saying here

00:19:27.045 --> 00:19:29.610
is that exercise can handle the
stress happening that you're

00:19:29.610 --> 00:19:31.810
picking up on each
new day, provided

00:19:31.810 --> 00:19:33.370
that you're
exercising every day.

00:19:33.370 --> 00:19:35.340
If you want to handle
the backlog of stresses

00:19:35.340 --> 00:19:37.506
that you've been accumulating
so that you can really

00:19:37.506 --> 00:19:39.510
start to perform at
100%, in this case,

00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:41.150
we need to de-excite
the nervous system

00:19:41.150 --> 00:19:43.850
and create order so we
can get that right side

00:19:43.850 --> 00:19:44.680
of the boiling pot.

00:19:48.930 --> 00:19:52.940
So everyone clear on that, about
when stress is good for you?

00:19:52.940 --> 00:19:55.844
When you're actually in a
life threatening situation.

00:19:55.844 --> 00:19:57.260
And it's good for
it to have them,

00:19:57.260 --> 00:20:00.260
but if it stays in your body
over a long period of time,

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:02.340
it can do any number of
terrible things to you.

00:20:02.340 --> 00:20:05.850
It's basically the equivalent
of pouring acid in your body.

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:07.780
Every time you get
stressed, every stressy

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:09.620
thought that you
have, it creates

00:20:09.620 --> 00:20:12.670
adrenaline and cortisol, which
are acidic stress chemicals.

00:20:12.670 --> 00:20:14.940
So it's like putting a penny
into a thing of Coca Cola

00:20:14.940 --> 00:20:16.280
or a thing of hydrochloric acid.

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:18.099
It's going to break
down prematurely.

00:20:18.099 --> 00:20:19.140
Same thing with our body.

00:20:19.140 --> 00:20:22.620
If you're stressed, your body
is going to age much faster than

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:26.080
if you are alkaline,
which is what?

00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:28.290
When you meditate,
your brain produces

00:20:28.290 --> 00:20:31.090
dopamine and serotonin, which
are bliss chemicals, which

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:33.540
are more alkaline in nature,
which can actually slow down

00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:36.070
the aging process.

