00:22:46.885 --> 00:22:49.040
go of the thing that's
pushing them forward?

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:49.410
EMILY FLETCHER: Yeah.

00:22:49.410 --> 00:22:50.490
It's a great question.

00:22:50.490 --> 00:22:52.710
And I think it's a
really valid concern

00:22:52.710 --> 00:22:55.780
because if you spent your
whole life only being motivated

00:22:55.780 --> 00:22:58.980
by adrenaline and only
being driven by anxiety

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:01.820
or competition, then
it's terrifying to lose

00:23:01.820 --> 00:23:04.520
that because you don't know
what's going to motivate you.

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:05.810
Now, the beautiful
thing that I have found

00:23:05.810 --> 00:23:07.935
is that as you start
meditating, you start actually

00:23:07.935 --> 00:23:09.590
wanting to move
towards the positive.

00:23:09.590 --> 00:23:13.780
You start being inspired by
and motivated by creativity

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:15.852
and creation for the
sake of innovation.

00:23:15.852 --> 00:23:17.560
But that's hard to
communicate to someone

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:19.680
who hasn't had that
visceral experience yet.

00:23:19.680 --> 00:23:23.152
So here's my analogy, and
please forgive me, y'all.

00:23:23.152 --> 00:23:24.360
I'm a really good tap dancer.

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:25.670
I am not a technician.

00:23:25.670 --> 00:23:27.320
But here goes.

00:23:27.320 --> 00:23:29.950
Let's imagine that the
brain is a computer.

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:30.700
OK?

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:32.885
And let's say that
you have 10 million--

00:23:32.885 --> 00:23:34.760
I don't even know if
this is possible-- let's

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:37.980
say you have 10 million open
windows on this computer, which

00:23:37.980 --> 00:23:40.260
is, PS, by the time
you're 20 years old,

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:41.890
you have something
like 10 million

00:23:41.890 --> 00:23:43.950
precognitive commitments
in your brain,

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:46.200
which basically means that
any time that you've gotten

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:49.830
stressed, it's left a little
open window in your brain.

00:23:49.830 --> 00:23:53.614
So let's say that Hulu and
GChat and YouTube and Facebook

00:23:53.614 --> 00:23:56.030
and Vimeo, and Vine-- you've
got all of these things open,

00:23:56.030 --> 00:23:58.070
and you're like, whew, maybe
I should get back to work,

00:23:58.070 --> 00:23:59.417
maybe I should write an email.

00:23:59.417 --> 00:24:01.250
And you go to write an
email, and the cursor

00:24:01.250 --> 00:24:02.615
is like 20 spaces behind.

00:24:02.615 --> 00:24:04.480
You're like, bleaugh,
stupid computer,

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:06.790
can't even type an email.

00:24:06.790 --> 00:24:09.760
Well, the computer is more than
capable of typing an email,

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:12.360
but you're spending so much of
that computing power running

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:15.080
those 10 million open
windows from the past

00:24:15.080 --> 00:24:17.390
that you're robbing yourself
of your full potential

00:24:17.390 --> 00:24:19.160
for the right now.

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:22.430
And every problem gets
solved in the right now.

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:24.580
Also, all of your
bliss and fulfillment

00:24:24.580 --> 00:24:26.250
is experienced in the right now.

00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:29.740
Eckhart Tolle wrote a whole book
about it, "The Power of Now."

00:24:29.740 --> 00:24:32.750
So I liken it, really, to
an overworked computer-- too

00:24:32.750 --> 00:24:34.520
many windows open
on the computer,

00:24:34.520 --> 00:24:37.310
and you're robbing yourself
of your full performance

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:37.930
capabilities.

00:24:37.930 --> 00:24:39.580
It's basically like
your body's so busy

00:24:39.580 --> 00:24:42.640
preparing for this
imaginary tiger attack

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:44.420
that you don't have
all of your resources

00:24:44.420 --> 00:24:47.440
available for whatever
your task at hand is.

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:48.736
Does that make sense?

00:24:48.736 --> 00:24:49.235
Great.

